                "description": "This address holds a rich layer of local musical history beneath its current function as a Social Security office. Before its demolition, this corner was the home of the Kabuki Sukiyaki restaurant and lounge in the late 1960s, a vital gathering space. This site is legendary in the local Chicano music scene: in 1969, East L.A. producer Eddie Davis discovered the house band playing a Latin-Jazz and R&B cover called 'Viva Tirado'. After being signed and renamed El Chicano, their track became a massive hit, cementing this exact location as the birthplace of the classic 'Eastside Sound'.",
