                "name": "Van Nuys HPOZ",
                "description": "Architectural Significance: The area acts as a timeline of early 20th-century suburban expansion. It begins with Craftsman and Colonial Revival homes, shifts to Spanish Colonial and English Revival in the 1920s, and transitions into Minimal Traditional and early California Ranch styles. Because the area was dominated by poultry farming in the 1920s, many of the lots are unusually deep to accommodate the historic chicken houses that once sat at the rear of the properties.\n\nThe History: Established in 2005, this was the very first Historic Preservation Overlay Zone (HPOZ) in the San Fernando Valley. It protects a neighborhood that features some of the earliest residential development in the Valley, with single-family homes dating back to 1911.",
